
[1]verdict

   VER'DICT, n. [L. verum dictum, true declaration.]

   1. The answer of a jury given to the court concerning any matter of
   face in any cause, civil or criminal, committed to their trial and
   examination. In criminal causes, the jury decide the law as well as the
   fact. Verdicts are general or special; general, when they decide in
   general terms, or in the terms of the general issue, as no wrong, no
   disseisin; special, when the jury find and state the facts at large,
   and as to the law, pray the judgment of the court.

   2. Decision; judgment; opinion pronounced; as, to be condemned by the
   verdict of the public.

   These enormities were condemned by the verdict of common humanity.
